Senator Barau Jibrin has been declared winner of the  All  Progressives Congress (APC) primary election for Kano North senatorial district. Jibrin, an incumbent, garnered all the 697 votes from 697 delegates to win the primary. It was gathered Governor Abdullahi Umar Ganduje had stepped down for Jibrin, thus easing his victory. The governor said his decision was part of the reconciliation efforts among the APC stakeholders in Kano.   Ex-minister Nweke is Enugu APGA governorship candidate     Niger Governor Bello defeats incumbent for senatorial ticket     Kwara lawmaker loses bid to return to Senate   Some delegates told reporters that they voted for Jibrin because of his footprints in the 16 local government areas under Kano Northern senatorial district in the last eight years of his tenure. Also, Senator Basheer Garba Lado, a leading aspirant on the platform of the APC for Kano Central senatorial seat, has rejected the result of the primaries conducted on Saturday, which Abdulsalam Abdulkarim Zaura reportedly won. Lado alleged that the election was “manipulated” to favour Zaura. In a statement over the exercise, the senator accused Governor Ganduje of “intimidating the delegates” to vote for Zaura. He said: “What this means in the face of the law is that no election took place on Saturday and, as such, there is no APC candidate for the district…”